body:
Consider the following code:
```systemverilog
package test;

  typedef enum int unsigned {
    Mode0 = 0,
    Mode1 = 1
  } mode_e;

  typedef struct packed {
    mode_e a;
    bit    b;
  } foo_t;

  parameter foo_t Foo0 = '{a: Mode0, b: 1'b0};
  parameter foo_t Foo1 = '{a: 0,     b: 1'b0};

endpackage
```

Verilator complains about the definition of `Foo0`:
```
> /opt/verilator-test/bin/verilator --lint-only test.sv
%Warning-WIDTHCONCAT: test.sv:13:38: Unsized numbers/parameters not allowed in concatenations.
   13 |   parameter foo_t Foo0 = '{a: Mode0, b: 1'b0};
      |                                      ^
                      ... Use "/* verilator lint_off WIDTHCONCAT */" and lint_on around source to disable this message.
%Error: Exiting due to 1 warning(s)
```

It seems that this is because it's treating `Mode0` as an unsized integer. However, it's fine with an explicit int (as passed to `Foo1`). It's also fine if I change the struct to contain an `int` instead of the enum type.

Changing `mode_t` to be `enum bit [1:0]` is a work-around that silences the warning, but I don't think this behaviour is quite consistent. Is there some "turn an enum value into an int" step missing somewhere?

EDIT: I forgot to give the verilator version. I'm seeing this with current tip of master (`Verilator 4.201 devel rev v4.200-39-g7ea014da`)
